
`TypeEnvironment` owns semantic type identity for a module.

`TypeId` equality in the active `TypeEnvironment` is the semantic comparison rule.
`DataType` is parse-only or diagnostic-only once a semantic type exists.

This rule is everywhere.
AST, HIR, borrow validation, backends and diagnostics all depend on it.

## Core paths

- `src/compiler_frontend/datatypes/` owns `TypeEnvironment`, builtin type IDs, constructed type shapes and semantic type lookup.
- `src/compiler_frontend/type_coercion/` owns implicit contextual compatibility and promotion rules layered on top of type identity.
- `src/compiler_frontend/value_mode.rs` tracks frontend access classification for bindings, expressions, call arguments and receivers.
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/type_resolution/` resolves parsed type references to canonical `TypeId`s.

`DataType` is syntax.
`TypeId` is semantics.
Keep that line sharp.

## What TypeEnvironment owns

`TypeEnvironment` contains the canonical module-local view of semantic types:

- builtins
- nominal structs
- choices
- options
- growable collections
- fixed-capacity collections
- hashmaps
- generic parameters and concrete generic instances
- external package types that have frontend mappings

AST builds the environment during AST environment construction.
HIR stores compact frontend `TypeId`s, then the lowered module travels with the paired `TypeEnvironment`.
Borrow validation and backends use that pair for semantic type queries.

## DataType boundaries

`DataType` remains useful at the syntax and diagnostic edge:

- parsed type annotations before semantic resolution
- source spelling in diagnostics when no semantic type exists yet
- helper payloads where the compiler is still reporting syntax shape

It must not be used for semantic decisions in executable AST or HIR.
If a semantic type exists, use `TypeId`.

## Collections and maps

Collection type identity is a canonical `TypeEnvironment` shape.
Growable `{T}` and fixed `{N T}` collections are distinct `TypeId`s.
Backends recover element type and optional fixed capacity through collection-shape queries, not parse syntax or backend side tables.

Hashmap type identity is a separate canonical constructed shape.
`{K = V}` maps store key and value `TypeId`s directly.
They are not represented as collection capacity variants.
They are not backend side tables.

This matters for both semantic checks and backend feature validation.
A backend can reject reachable hashmap use by querying validated HIR and the paired type environment, not by re-reading source literals.

## Nominal types and members

`TypeEnvironment` is built during AST environment construction and populated before AST body emission begins.
Early nominal registration records identity and generic parameter metadata first, so constructors are name-resolvable before every field and variant shell has been semantically checked.

Canonical field and variant members are written after AST-owned constructor shells resolve to semantic `TypeId`s.
Unresolved field and variant shells stay in AST-owned side tables until then.

Member queries should use borrowed field/variant views and direct lookup helpers.
AST, HIR and backend-facing lowering should not clone member lists just to do semantic lookup.

## Function signatures

Function signatures store canonical `TypeId`s on `ReturnSlot` and `Declaration` after resolution.
Parallel `DataType` values may remain available for diagnostics only.

That lets call validation, HIR lowering and backend validation use semantic identity while diagnostics can still render useful source-level names.

## External package types

External package types with frontend mappings get normal semantic `TypeId`s.
External package parameters that have no frontend mapping use `ExpectedParameterType::UnknownExternal` instead of sentinel type IDs.
Call validation skips ordinary type compatibility for unknown external parameters because the frontend has no semantic type to compare.

Don't invent fake `TypeId`s for unknown externals.
Unknown external means exactly that.

## Contextual coercion

Expression evaluation determines the natural type of an expression and stays strict.
Contextual coercion applies only at frontend sites that own a boundary.

Boundary owners include:

- declarations
- assignments
- returns
- template/string content
- explicit `cast` target boundaries
- backend/prelude call contracts
- struct and choice fields
- typed collection and map entries
- default values

`type_coercion` owns implicit contextual compatibility and promotion rules.
Explicit `cast` resolution is AST-owned and uses compiler-owned cast policy/evidence metadata instead of the coercion path.

## Value mode isn't type identity

`value_mode.rs` tracks frontend access classification.
It helps classify bindings, expressions, call arguments and receiver use.

It keeps mutability/reference state separate from `DataType`.
Runtime ownership is a later borrow/lowering concern.

That split is deliberate.
A `~T` parameter and a `T` parameter don't mean the type system has two runtime type identities for `T`.
They mean the call boundary has a different access mode.

## HIR and validation

HIR `HirStruct` and `HirChoice` carry `frontend_type_id` to trace lowering-local layouts back to the canonical `TypeEnvironment` entry.
Validation asserts those IDs resolve to real type definitions.

HIR validation also checks frontend `TypeId` links, expression invariants and region graph shape before borrow validation or backend feature validation sees the module.
A broken type link in HIR is a compiler invariant failure, not a user diagnostic.

## Common mistakes

- Comparing types through `DataType` after semantic resolution.
- Formatting type names early instead of rendering through `DiagnosticRenderContext`.
- Treating fixed collection capacity as an allocation hint rather than semantic type identity.
- Modelling hashmaps as collection variants.
- Letting a backend recover type meaning from parse syntax.
- Using mutability/access mode as if it were a separate type identity.
- Creating sentinel `TypeId`s for unknown external package parameters.

